The following functions will be used to change a char date to a date format, add the president to a dataset, and use binary indicators to identify presidents.

add_date <- function(df) {
  # formats the data to have the date as a date 
  df <- df |>  
    mutate(ymd=as.Date(paste(ym, "-20", sep=""))) |> 
    select(-ym)
  }
add_pres <- function(df) {
  bush_end <- as.Date("2009-01-20")
  trump_start <- as.Date("2017-01-20")
  
  df$president <- 
    ifelse(df$ymd >= bush_end & df$ymd < trump_start, "obama", 
           ifelse(df$ymd < bush_end, "bush", "trump")) 
  
  return(df)
}
zero_or_one <- function(df) {
  df$bush <- 
    ifelse(df$president == "bush", 1, 0) 
  df$obama <- 
    ifelse(df$president == "obama", 1, 0) 
  df$trump <- 
    ifelse(df$president == "trump", 1, 0) 
  
  return(df)
}
plot_4 <- function(df, start, end) {
  df |>
    ggplot(aes(x = ymd, y = trends, color = president)) +
    geom_point(shape = 1) +
    geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE) + 
    ylim(start, end) +
    xlab("Year") +
    ylab("Google Trends")
}

While there was a little change in the daily duration of immigration coverage between the pre-campaign and campaign periods, there was a significant increase after the inauguration, especially on FOX News. While there was a modest post-inauguration increase in immigration coverage on CNN and MSNBC, Fox News average monthly number of immigration segments nearly doubled after the inauguration, from 303.5 to 545.3. This suggests that a substantial portion, if not all, of the news effects we measure can be attributed to stories originated from Fox and other forms of right-wing media, many of which are extremely anti-immigrants.
